Response 1

In Excel, you can use a combination of the INDIRECT and SHEET functions to achieve a lookup based on the sheet name. Here's a generic formula that you can use:\n\nexcel\n=INDIRECT("'" & sheet_name & "'!" & "A1")\n\n\nReplace sheet_name with the reference to the cell containing the sheet name you want to look up. The formula assumes that you want to retrieve the value from cell A1 in the specified sheet.\n\nFor example, if your sheet names are in column Z, and you want to look up the value from cell A1 in the sheet specified in cell Z1, your formula would be:\n\nexcel\n=INDIRECT("'" & Z1 & "'!" & "A1")\n\n\nRemember that the INDIRECT function is volatile, which means it recalculates every time there is a change in the workbook. If you have a large dataset, frequent recalculations might impact performance.

Response 2

There are a couple of ways to achieve this, depending on your specific needs and spreadsheet software:

1. Using INDIRECT and VLOOKUP:

This approach is best if you have a limited number of sheets and want to lookup a specific value in the same cell across those sheets.

Here's the formula:

=VLOOKUP(lookup_value, INDIRECT("'"&sheet_name&"'!cell_range"), col_index, FALSE)
  • lookup_value: The value you want to find.
  • sheet_name: The name of the sheet you want to search in. This can be a cell reference containing the sheet name, or it can be directly entered as a string within quotes.
  • cell_range: The range of cells where you want to search for the lookup_value. For example, A1:B10 would search both A and B columns from row 1 to 10.
  • col_index: The column index of the value you want to return. If the lookup_value is found in the first column, col_index would be 1.

2. Using SUMPRODUCT and ISNUMBER:

This approach is more flexible and can handle a large number of sheets. It sums the values you want to find across all sheets, multiplied by a mask that ensures only values from the desired sheet are included.

Here's the formula:

=SUMPRODUCT(--(ISNUMBER(INDIRECT("'"&sheet_names&"'!cell_range"))), INDIRECT("'"&sheet_names&"'!cell_range"))

  • sheet_names: A range containing the names of all sheets you want to search. This can be a list of sheet names separated by commas within quotes (e.g., "'Sheet1,Sheet2,Sheet3'"), or a cell range containing the sheet names.
  • cell_range: Same as in the previous approach.

3. Using INDEX and MATCH with array formula:

This approach is similar to the SUMPRODUCT method but uses INDEX and MATCH to find the specific cell instead of summing all values.

Here's the formula:

=INDEX(sheet_names, MATCH(TRUE, --(ISNUMBER(INDIRECT("'"&sheet_names&"'!cell_range"))), 0))
  • sheet_names: Same as in the SUMPRODUCT approach.
  • cell_range: Same as in the previous approaches.

Remember to adjust the formulas and ranges based on your specific needs and software. Make sure to replace the placeholders with your actual values and sheet references.

I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any other questions.

Privacy Preference Center

When you visit any website, it may store or retrieve information on your browser, mostly in the form of cookies. This information might be about you, your preferences or your device and is mostly used to make the site work as you expect it to. The information does not usually directly identify you, but it can give you a more personalized web experience. Because we respect your right to privacy, you can choose not to allow some types of cookies. Click on the different category headings to find out more and change our default settings. However, blocking some types of cookies may impact your experience of the site and the services we are able to offer.

Manage Consent Preferences

Strictly Necessary Cookies

Always Active

These cookies are necessary for the website to function. They are usually only set in response to actions made by you which amount to a request for services, such as setting your privacy preferences, logging in or filling in forms.

Performance Cookies

These cookies allow us to count visits and traffic sources so we can measure and improve the performance of our site. They help us understand how visitors move around the site and which pages are most frequently visited.

Functional Cookies

These cookies are used to record your choices and settings, maintain your preferences over time and recognize you when you return to our website. These cookies help us to personalize our content for you and remember your preferences.

Targeting Cookies

These cookies are deployed to our site by our advertising partners to build a profile of your interests and provide you with content that is relevant to you, including to show you relevant ads on other sites.
